    <h2>Pre-Historical Era</h2>

    <p>
      Long before its establishment as a protected area, the Kanha region was inhabited by tribal
      communities including the Gond and Baiga peoples. These communities had a symbiotic relationship
      with the forest, practicing sustainable forest management and traditional conservation practices.
    </p>

    <h3>Gond Kingdom Era</h3>
    <p>
      The region was part of the broader Gondwana kingdom, with the Baiga and Gond tribes considering
      the forests sacred. Traditional taboos against over-hunting helped maintain wildlife populations
      during this period.
    </p>

    <h3>Colonial Hunting Era (19th Century)</h3>
    <p>
      The British colonial period saw extensive hunting by royalty and British officials. Records from
      the 1880s-1920s describe grand hunts with hundreds of tigers and other big game killed. This
      period significantly depleted wildlife populations, particularly tigers.
    </p>

    <h2>Conservation Era Begins</h2>

    <h3>1933: Wildlife Sanctuary Establishment</h3>
    <p>
      Concerned by declining wildlife populations, the British administration declared the area a
      wildlife sanctuary in 1933. This marked the beginning of formal protection efforts, though
      enforcement was limited and hunting continued in surrounding areas.
    </p>

    <h3>1947: Independence and Forest Department</h3>
    <p>
      After India's independence in 1947, forest management came under the newly formed Forest
      Department. Initial efforts focused on regulating hunting and establishing forest protection
      mechanisms. However, habitat loss and poaching continued to threaten wildlife.
    </p>

    <h3>1955: National Park Declaration</h3>
    <p>
      On June 1, 1955, the area was officially declared a National Park, giving it stronger legal
      protection. This declaration was part of India's broader conservation movement following
      independence, recognizing the need to protect India's wildlife heritage.
    </p>

    <Backlink       title="Experience Kanha's Living History"
      description="Wildmark Resort near Khatia Gate offers safari experiences in this historic conservation landscape. Book a package to see the success of decades of conservation work."
      primaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/wildlife-of-kanha-national-park-beyond-the-tiger/"
      primaryAnchor="Kanha Park History & Wildlife"
      secondaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/"
      secondaryAnchor="Book Kanha Heritage Safari"
      tertiaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/faq/"
      tertiaryAnchor="Kanha History FAQ"
