    <h2>Project Tiger Era (1973-Present)</h2>

    <h3>The Conservation Crisis of the Early 1970s</h3>
    <p>
      By the early 1970s, India's wildlife faced an unprecedented crisis:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Tiger population dropped to approximately 1,800 nationwide</li>
      <li>Habitat loss accelerating due to development</li>
      <li>Poaching for skins and traditional medicines</li>
      <li>Many reserves existed only on paper with limited protection</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1973: Project Tiger Launched</h3>
    <p>
      On November 15, 1973, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi launched Project Tiger, designating nine
      tiger reserves across India. Kanha was among these original nine, marking the beginning of
      India's flagship tiger conservation program.
    </p>

    <h3>Project Tiger Implementation at Kanha</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha implemented several key Project Tiger components:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Core Zone Protection:</strong> Strict protection of prime tiger habitat</li>
      <li><strong>Buffer Zone Management:</strong> Sustainable use of surrounding areas</li>
      <li><strong>Anti-Poaching Patrols:</strong> Armed forest guards protecting wildlife</li>
      <li><strong>Habitat Management:</strong> Controlled burning, grassland management</li>
      <li><strong>Scientific Monitoring:</strong> Tiger population censuses and research</li>
      <li><strong>Community Engagement:</strong> Relocation programs for forest villages</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>1970s: Barasingha Crisis</h3>
    <p>
      In 1970, the hard-ground Barasingha population crashed to just 66 animals due to:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Habitat degradation from vegetation succession</li>
      <li>Disease outbreaks</li>
      <li>Predation pressure</li>
      <li>Competition with livestock</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1970s-1980s: Barasingha Recovery Program</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha launched a dedicated Barasingha conservation program:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Habitat Management:</strong> Meadow restoration through controlled burning and grass cutting</li>
      <li><strong>Veterinary Care:</strong> Treatment of sick and injured animals</li>
      <li><strong>Captive Breeding:</strong> Breeding program for injured individuals unable to survive in wild</li>
      <li><strong>Population Monitoring:</strong> Regular censuses to track recovery</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conservation Success Timeline</h2>

    <h3>1970s Milestones</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1970:</strong> Barasingha population at 66 (crisis low)</li>
      <li><strong>1973:</strong> Project Tiger launched at Kanha</li>
      <li><strong>1976:</strong> First tiger census shows 50-60 tigers</li>
      <li><strong>1978:</strong> Barasingha population crosses 100</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1980s Milestones</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1982:</strong> Kanha expanded to current boundaries</li>
      <li><strong>1985:</strong> Tiger population reaches 80-90</li>
      <li><strong>1988:</strong> Barasingha population at 300+</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1990s Milestones</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1993:</strong> Tourism infrastructure developed</li>
      <li><strong>1995:</strong> Tiger population crosses 100</li>
      <li><strong>1998:</strong> Barasingha population at 500+</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2000s-Present Milestones</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>2006:</strong> Buffer zone added (1,067 sq km)</li>
      <li><strong>2010:</strong> Barasingha population reaches 700+</li>
      <li><strong>2018:</strong> Eco-tourism zones designated</li>
      <li><strong>2024:</strong> Tiger population at 125, Barasingha at 800+</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The Jungle Book Legacy</h2>

    <p>
      The broader forests of the Satpura-Maikal landscape, including areas adjacent to Kanha, are
      believed to have inspired Rudyard Kipling's "The Jungle Book" (1894). While the exact setting
      remains debated, the Seoni forests near Kanha are widely associated with Mowgli's jungle,
      giving the park international cultural recognition.
    </p>

    <p>
      This literary connection has helped Kanha:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Attract international visitors and researchers</li>
      <li>Generate conservation funding through tourism</li>
      <li>Create cultural value beyond ecological importance</li>
      <li>Inspire wildlife films and documentaries</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Modern Conservation Challenges</h2>

    <p>
      Despite its conservation success, Kanha faces ongoing challenges:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Habitat Fragmentation:</strong> From development outside park boundaries</li>
      <li><strong>Climate Change:</strong> Affecting water sources and vegetation</li>
      <li><strong>Human-Wildlife Conflict:</strong> With surrounding villages</li>
      <li><strong>Tourism Pressure:</strong> Managing increasing visitor numbers</li>
      <li><strong>Genetic Diversity:</strong> Maintaining healthy tiger populations</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Kanha's Global Conservation Impact</h2>

    <p>
      Kanha's conservation success has influenced wildlife protection globally:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Model for Tiger Conservation:</strong> Cited in international tiger recovery programs</li>
      <li><strong>Barasingha Recovery:</strong> Template for ungulate conservation</li>
      <li><strong>Project Tiger Success:</strong> Demonstrated effectiveness of protected area management</li>
      <li><strong>Research Hub:</strong> Decades of scientific data informing conservation policy</li>
      <li><strong>Tourism Model:</strong> Balanced approach to wildlife tourism and conservation</li>
    </ul>

